what did i do today 

A single HTML file that practically demonstrates every CSS concept learned today — each concept in its own section with a live visual example.

What I Implemented
1. Inline Style

Applied CSS directly inside HTML tags using style attribute
Saw how it overrides all other styles
Understood why it is bad practice for large projects
Used it only to demonstrate the concept

2. Color Property

Applied colors using all four methods on real elements
Named colors — simple but limited options
HEX colors — most common in real projects
RGB colors — more control over values
RGBA colors — same as RGB but with opacity control
Applied both color for text and background-color for backgrounds

3. Text Properties

Practiced all text properties on different paragraphs
font-size — changed sizes across multiple elements
font-weight — from thin 100 to heavy 900
font-family — switched between Arial and Georgia
font-style — applied italic to selected text
text-align — left, center, right, justify on different blocks
text-decoration — underline and line-through
text-transform — uppercase and capitalize
letter-spacing — increased spacing for headings
line-height — improved readability of paragraphs

4. Element Selector

Styled all <p>, <h1>, <body> tags globally
Saw how one rule affects all matching elements on the page
Used it for base styles like font-family and background-color

5. Class Selector

Created reusable classes like .card, .container, .section-box
Applied same class to multiple elements
Applied multiple classes to one element
Understood this is the most used selector in real projects

6. ID Selector

Used #page-header and #page-footer for unique sections
Saw how ID has higher priority than class
Confirmed that ID must only appear once per page

7. Descendant Selector

Used div p to target all paragraphs inside a div
Saw it targets ALL levels deep — not just direct children
Applied different color to text inside specific containers

8. Adjacent Sibling Selector

Used h2 + p to style the first paragraph after every heading
Saw it only affects the immediately next sibling
Used it to add introductory paragraph styles automatically

9. Child Combinator

Used ul > li to target only direct list items
Compared with descendant selector to see the difference
Child combinator did not affect nested lists inside list items

10. Box Model

Visualised the four layers on actual elements
Applied different padding and margin values
Used box-sizing: border-box so padding does not add to width
Saw how margin creates space outside the element
Saw how padding creates space inside the element

11. Height and Width

Set fixed width and height on card elements
Used percentage width for responsive containers
Used max-width to prevent elements from stretching too wide
Learned not to set fixed height on containers with text

12. Border

Applied border shorthand on multiple elements
Practiced all border styles — solid, dashed, dotted
Used border-radius to round corners
Applied individual borders — only bottom border on headings
Used border as a visual divider between sections

13. Sides

Practiced all shorthand patterns for padding and margin
One value — all four sides same
Two values — top-bottom and left-right
Four values — top right bottom left clockwise
Applied individual side properties like padding-top and margin-left


Key Observations From Practical

Box model is the foundation of every layout — every element is a box
Class selector is used 90% of the time in real projects
Descendant and child selectors look similar but behave very differently
Inline styles are powerful but create maintenance problems
box-sizing: border-box should always be set on every project
Specificity decides which style wins when two rules conflict


Mistakes I Made During Practical

Set fixed height on a text container — content overflowed outside the box
Applied same ID to two elements — second one did not get styled
Used descendant selector expecting only direct children to be affected
Forgot box-sizing: border-box — padding was adding extra width

How I Fixed Them

Removed fixed height — let content determine the height naturally
Changed duplicate ID to a class
Switched to child combinator > when I needed only direct children
Added box-sizing: border-box to the universal selector at the top


Reflection
The practical made every concept click. Reading about the box model is one
thing — actually seeing padding push content inward and margin push elements
apart is completely different. The selector comparison section was the most
useful — putting descendant, child, and sibling selectors side by side made
their differences obvious. CSS starts to feel logical once you understand
that every element is a box and selectors are just ways to find the right box.
